⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 66/120 – Remove Duplicate Records (Keep Latest)

🎤 Interview Question

A customer table contains multiple records for the same customer.

Write PySpark code to keep only the latest record based on updated_date.


---

📊 Input Dataset

customer_id	name	updated_date

101	John	2024-01-10
101	John	2024-03-15
102	David	2024-02-20
102	David	2024-01-18



---

✅ Expected Output

customer_id	name	updated_date

101	John	2024-03-15
102	David	2024-02-20



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number, col

window_spec = (
    Window.partitionBy("customer_id")
          .orderBy(col("updated_date").desc())
)

result = (
    df.withColumn("rn", row_number().over(window_spec))
      .filter(col("rn") == 1)
      .drop("rn")
)

result.show()


---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. Why not use dropDuplicates()?

Answer

dropDuplicates() keeps an arbitrary record.

It does not guarantee that the latest record is retained.


---

Q2. Why is this solution preferred?

Answer

It explicitly orders records by updated_date, ensuring the latest record is selected.


---

Q3. Real-world use cases?

Answer

Customer master data

Product catalog updates

Employee records

CDC pipelines



